    </div>

    <p>The bioactive compound primarily responsible for cordyceps' energy effects is cordycepin (3'-deoxyadenosine), which structurally resembles adenosine and upregulates ATP synthesis via the adenylate cyclase pathway. Additionally, cordyceps polysaccharides improve mitochondrial membrane potential, enhancing the efficiency of the electron transport chain where ATP is generated. A second key species — lion's mane (<em>Hericium erinaceus</em>) — complements cordyceps by boosting mental energy through NGF (nerve growth factor) stimulation, supporting focus and cognitive stamina alongside physical endurance.</p>

